# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>Given the supreme performance and sterling reputation of the Marauder, it was only natural for the Clans to devote resources to developing a successor worthy of the name. Before the advent of Omni technology and the creation of the Timber Wolf, that title belonged to the Marauder IIC. Built from the ground up in its progenitor's image, the eighty-five-ton Marauder IIC took full advantage of the cutting-edge technology available in 2828 to enhance every aspect of the original. The result was a bigger, stronger, more resilient and durable Marauder, one that remains popular even today, despite its classification as a second-line BattleMech.</p><p>Ten tons heavier than its Inner Sphere ancestor, the Marauder IIC pushed the design into the assault weight class while retaining the speed and silhouette that made the original so feared. The soundness of its original engineering is evident in its enduring service record, and the design has since spread across multiple Clans through trade, isorla, and independent production.</p>

capabilities:<p>While structurally similar to the original Marauder, the advanced capabilities of Golden Century Clan technology expanded the BattleMech's chassis to accommodate its improvements. Emphasizing a balance of long-reaching, high-yield firepower, solid armor, and mobility to keep up with supporting units, the Marauder IIC followed in its progenitor's massive footsteps. The Clans' preference for high-power energy weapons over ballistics and missiles enabled the design to remain effective almost indefinitely in the hands of an expert MechWarrior, securing its role as an ideal command 'Mech among the glory-seeking warriors of the Clan officer corps.</p><p>The weapon layout is typical of the standard Marauder, each pod-like forearm carrying an ER PPC paired with a Medium Pulse Laser. The torso weaponry replaces the original's top-mounted autocannon with a third ER PPC, eliminating ammunition dependency entirely. Four ER Small Lasers provide close-range defense, while twenty-one double heat sinks keep heat levels manageable through volley fire. Eleven and a half tons of Forging MD4 ferro-fibrous armor provides superior protection, with the Type 850 Light endo steel frame freeing critical tonnage. The Consolidated Fusion 340 engine drives the assault 'Mech to a respectable sixty-four kilometers per hour, matching the original Marauder's ground speed.</p>

deployment:<p>Following the poor staying power of the IIC 4, Gorton, Kingsley &amp; Thorpe looked to the Viking for inspiration and revamped the Marauder IIC as a powerful direct-fire support 'Mech. Introduced in 3081, the IIC 7 drops ground speed to fifty-four kilometers per hour via a smaller 255-rated XL engine in favor of a devastating weapons array. A Targeting Computer guides the Type 0 HAG 30, Omega 12-Coil Gauss Rifle, Kolibri Delta Series Large Pulse Laser, and Series 1g ER Small Laser, while twin Smartshot Mk V Streak SRM-4 launchers keep battle armor at bay. An ECM Suite jams enemy targeting systems. Sixteen and a half tons of Compound 12A1 standard armor provides maximum protection for the chassis. Draconis Combine field reports recommend using artillery to dislodge a dug-in IIC 7, as the 'Mech has proven highly effective against aircraft attempting to bomb it out of position.</p>

history:<p>The Marauder IIC's development came in 2828, the same year the Second Succession War erupted across the Inner Sphere. While the Great Houses tore each other apart, the Clans channeled their resources into perfecting the designs taken on Operation Exodus. The Marauder, long favored by SLDF regulars, Royal units, and the elite Gunslinger program, was an obvious candidate for enhancement. The resulting IIC variant represented the pinnacle of Clan weapons technology prior to the advent of the OmniMech.</p><p>For over two centuries the base design remained unchanged, proof of the thoroughness of its original engineering. It was not until the emergence of new weapons technology in the 3050s and 3060s that the first production variants appeared. Clan Star Adder introduced a visually refreshed model carrying newly developed Heavy Lasers, motivated in part by their desire to humiliate Clan Blood Spirit following the Absorption of Clan Burrock. This upgraded Marauder IIC quickly spread through the Home Clans, with the Cloud Cobras, Goliath Scorpions, Snow Ravens, Blood Spirits, and Diamond Sharks all acquiring examples.</p><p>The mercantile efforts of Clan Diamond Shark proved instrumental in spreading the design to the Inner Sphere–based Invading Clans. However, when a shadow trade war between the Diamond Sharks and Clan Ghost Bear cut off supply in the 3060s, the Rasalhague Dominion established its own production at Gorton, Kingsley &amp; Thorpe Enterprises on Satalice. Clan Jade Falcon similarly began manufacturing at Olivetti Weaponry on Sudeten, constructing a new line adjacent to the venerable Turkina facility.</p><p>Heavy combat throughout the Jihad spread multiple variants across the Lyran front and beyond. During the liberation of Robinson by the Republic of the Sphere, two lances of Marauder IICs from the Eleventh and Twelfth Principes took part in the hard-fought siege of Bueller, accounting for over fifteen BattleMech kills against the Draconis Combine's Seventh Sword of Light. Although half were lost after Combine reinforcements arrived, the heavy stream of near-continuous PPC fire from the IICs helped hold the line long enough for additional Republic forces to smash the Combine flanks.</p><p>The Marauder IIC continues to be built in its original layout by the Jade Falcons, joining the Rasalhague Dominion's models as the formidable core of many Clan assault formations. In the wake of Operation Revival, the Falcons reintroduced ancient variants incorporating missile launchers, while Olivetti's most modern incarnation reinstates the chassis's traditional beam weaponry alongside an XL engine and improved jump jets.</p>

